<subSubSection id="C337656CFFB1FFA7FD97FDDCFB050965" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9236E7FFB1FFA7FD97FDDCFB050965" blockId="20.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="B959EAF5FFB1FFA7FD97FDDCFE8F0908" bold="true" box="[199,328,1015,1040]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="B959EAF5FFB1FFA7FD97FDDCFE850908" bold="true" box="[199,322,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Comments</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D64FFB1FFA7FC1FFDD3FD830908" authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[335,580,1016,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyropanda">
<emphasis id="B959EAF5FFB1FFA7FC1FFDD3FD830908" box="[335,580,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Aptilotella pyropanda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily recognized by the fiery orange thorax and legs. In dorsal view, the highly reflective silvery-white spots of the ocular emarginations and lunule give the fly an appearance of having three “headlights.” This species has a relatively broad range with at least two populations along the Sierra Madre de Chiapas Mountains, one in the extreme Mexican southeast and the other in western 
<collectingCountry id="F33A7677FFB1FFA7F911FA4FFB790965" box="[1089,1214,1124,1149]" name="Guatemala" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
